default10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default“Food sovereignty is the right of peoples to healthy and culturally appropriate food produced through ecologically sound and sustainable methods, and their right to define their own food and agriculture systems. It puts the aspirations and needs of tho
defaultse who produce, distribute and consume food at the heart of food systems and policies rather than the demands of markets and corporations.”
default11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe world already produces enough food to be able to feed everybody.
default It is over a decade since the then UN Special 
defaultRapporteur on the Right to Food, Jean Ziegler, noted that the world already produced enough food to feed 12 billion people,
default and food production has increased since then.
default The problem is access to food and the means for its production.
default Increasing productio
defaultn, per se, will not alter levels of hunger, if those who are food insecure or are malnourished continue to be unable to afford adequate nutritious food: reducing poverty is the most effective way to improve food security. 
defaultOne aspect of this is policies to 
defaultsupport the ability of 
defaultsmall-scale farmers, in the UK as well as elsewhere in the world, to make decent living.
default12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSupport for biodiverse small
default-
defaultscale and ecological producers is vital for UK and EU food security because genetic diversity is critical for resil
defaultience to pests and other challenges which are likely to get worse with climate change. The Irish potato famine was caused by Ireland’s dependence on very few varieties of potato – making the crop very susceptible to disease. 
defaultIndigenous and local plant vari
defaulteties
default in the field continue to evolve and adapt to environmental change unlike those in gene banks, making them more resilient. Thus, centres of genetic diversity
default,
default 
defaultsuch as potatoes in the Andes,
default are important for the UK and EU’s food security and economy.
