default37
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGM crops have not provided yield improvements, are 
defaultmainly developed for industrial commodity production, and facilitate increased concentration of power over agriculture by biotech corporations. They do not provide any nutritional advantage that cannot better be realised through diverse diets provided by b
defaultiodiverse food production. They have no role in any part of the solution for a sustainable and equitable food system in the UK or elsewhere. With regard to biotechnological research and development, the Precautionary Principle / Approach should prevail.
default38
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGe
defaultnetically modifie
defaultd
default crops are frequently put forward as an essential tool for securing food supply in the future
default.
default However, despite four decades of development GM crops, only two GM traits, herbicide tolerance and insect resistance(Bt), in mainly soya, maiz
defaulte, oilseed rape and cotton account, for about 99% of the GM crops grown commercially, predominantly used for animal feed , agrofuels and fibre production.
default39
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHerbicide tolerance (HT) and insect resistance (IR) are relative simple traits to genetically enginee
defaultr because they only code for additional novel proteins within the plant.  These are agronomic traits which produce some short-term savings for farmers until weeds and insects developed resistance to the herbicides and the Bt toxins. There is no evidence th
defaultat the addition of these GM traits has improved crop yields as compared with non-GM varieties. Indeed a comparison of maize and oilseed rape yield in predominantly GM USA and predominantly non-GM EU showed that the former has lagged behind in terms of annu
defaultal yield increment since th
defaulte advent of commercial GM crops.
default40
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMetabolic changes, intended and unintended, in GM crops raise the possibility of harmful changes taking place which require detailed assessment during risk assessments before crops can be approve
defaultd to enter the food/feed chain. In addition, the direct application of herbicides on GM HT crops will increase exposure to toxic residues in the end food/feed product.
default41
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore complex traits such as genes to produce beta carotene (for instance in Golden Rice)
default, drought tolerance, saline tolerance and nitrogen fixation have proved to be much more difficult to develop because they seek to alter the metabolism of crop plants in a way that may have unexpected consequences in other biochemical pathways of the receiv
defaulting plants.
default42
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGolden Rice cannot deliver the required amounts of vitamin A to people of a nutrient poor diet. The low levels of fat and oil in diets of poor people will also limit the conversion efficiency into Vitamin A. In the case of GM nitrogen-fixing ce
defaultreals, little progress has been made over the last three decades. To achieve this objective, both the plant and N fixing bacterium have to be genetically modified to form a symbiotic relationship. It is worth noting that during evolutionary history, grass/
defaultcereal species have never naturally evolved nitrogen fixing. The reason for this may lie in the high energy requirement for fixing nitrogen from the atmosphere which would divert significant amounts of sugars in cereals away for other functions such as gra
defaultin formation. The consequence may be lower yield
defaults.
default 
