default44
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA key part of successful agroecological approaches is formed by policies and practices that will sustain agricultural biodiversity. Thi
defaults is generated by and underpins agroecological production systems. Agricultural biodiversity comprises the diversity of seeds, plants, livestock breeds and fish and other aquatic organisms used for food and of the associated pollinators, pest predators and
default soil organisms. Agricultural biodiversity is the component of biodiversity that has been developed by and has co-evolved with people, and it underpins the food system and the wider economy, human health, the security of food supplies, and the viability of
default the biosphere. It is therefore essential to regulate, transform or prohibit any systems, methods, processes or technologies, which might damage or restrict agricultural biodiversity 
defaultand
default its related ecosystem functions. In order to develop agricultural bio
defaultdiversity, priority should be given to in situ conservation and development of domesticated species on-
defaultfarm, on the range and in rivers, ponds and lakes, by small-scale food producers, respecting their Farmers’
default Rights
default and related
default rights
default.
default 
